This change depends on a change that failed to merge.

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

IIRC we do not do this because we do not know the image size at this point due to potential image conversion down the flow. This will break image import when conversion is happening due to the validation during upload.

Clearly yet another case we do not test.

Patch Set 4:

> IIRC we do not do this because we do not know the image size at this point due to potential image conversion down the flow. This will break image import when conversion is happening due to the validation during upload.

The patch below this updates image size after conversion, FWIW. We do run across that in tests, which is why that patch has to come before this one in the stack. If you reorder them, you'll see that this one causes a test failure.

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> The patch below this updates image size after conversion, FWIW. We do run across that in tests, which is why that patch has to come before this one in the stack. If you reorder them, you'll see that this one causes a test failure.

Thanks! Good to know we actually tested and caught it. Also good to know that the size is something we can fix, I wasn't sure if it was one of those properties that could be set only once. (As there's been debate about the size and being able to set it from the user input.)

Maybe combining these two patches to make the relation, the fix to the issue and the change easier to review and identify?

Patch Set 4:

> Good to know we actually tested and caught it.

Note that it hasn't been until recently. When I added the import-testing tempest jobs, I configured one to enable image conversion so we get the cirros image converted during devstack setup. So that's where this patch originally failed before I made the one below it. All the testing locally worked fine, since I didn't have that configured. It doesn't look like we have a very comprehensive test for conversion in the tree, so maybe that's something that could be improved.

> Maybe combining these two patches to make the relation, the fix to the issue and the change easier to review and identify?

I like them to be separate so we get testing on each step and aren't in danger of changing several things at once and hiding an upgrade issue. But, I'll make a note on each to make it clear that they're additive and related.
